TEXT -1880 528 Left 2 ;wire-up and label the other block output (e.g., vz,\nvbmirror, etc.) as needed (e.g., for debugging, etc.)
TEXT -968 400 Left 2 ;single-ended class AB amplifier symbol
TEXT -256 -488 Left 2 ;get ground bias current from I(V1);\nuse the .meas value of groundcurrent
TEXT 1144 -1520 Left 2 !.options plotwinsize=0 numdgt=15 measdgt=15\n;.options srcsteps=0\n;.options GMIN=1e-6\n;.ic V(vinneg)={vcm}\n \n.op\n \n;if using newer versions of LTSpice, you may need to use the option \n;below to view the mosfet device operating points in the spice error log\n.options logopinfo\n \n.meas groundcurrent param I(V1)\n.meas iqn param I(V2)\n.meas iqp param I(V3)\n.meas voutmeas param V(vout)\n.meas ioffset param I(V7)\n.meas vinneg param V(vinneg)\n \n.param vdd=3.3\n.param vcm={vdd/2}\n.param iunitval=10u isubtractval={4*iunitval}\n.param rlval=50 clval=10p\n.param idacunitval=50u i1=12\n \n;idacval is the only parameter you should need to change;\n;note that idacval=0 is the default setting for this parameter\n.param idacval=0\n;.param idacval={i1*idacunitval}\n;.param idacval={-i1*idacunitval}
TEXT -80 -208 Left 2 ;subtracting away the four unit current \nsources used in the bias network
TEXT 1152 -656 Left 2 ;don't change any of these parameter values except for idacval;\nread the instructions, very carefully, about when to change this
TEXT 1144 -1760 Left 2 !;type the name of your .txt model file below;\n;the name of your model file should go before the .txt\n.lib model_file_01.txt
TEXT -2264 -1832 Left 2 ;line_driver_testbench_01.asc\n \nuse this basic DC performance testbench for the following (note that the \nidacval parameter should be set to zero for all items below except for item 8; \nsee item 8 for more information about when to change the idacval parameter):\n \n1) get the ground current value for your design from the .meas statement, and \nlist it in mA with 4 decimal places of precision (the lower, the better); you should\nonly report the ground current value for when the idacval parameter is set to zero\n(see item 8 for more information about when to change the idacval parameter)\n \n2) view the spice error log and ensure that all of your devices are in the proper\noperating mode -- most devices should be in saturation/active mode, but there\nwill be some exceptions, e.g., the triode resistor devices; note that one or both \nof your class AB output devices may (or may not) be in subthreshold mode: if \nso, and you think this is problematic for your design and you don't know how to\nresolve the issue, let me know (idacval should be zero for this)\n \n3) get the quiescent current values for your NMOS and PMOS class AB output\ndevices M1out and M2out, respectively, in the 0 V ammeters V2 and V3; report\nthe .meas statement values for iqn and iqp in mA with four decimal places of\nprecision; your measured values should be very close to your target IQ value\n(idacval should be zero for this)\n \n4) verify that vout is very near the common-mode voltage of VDD/2=1.65V; use\nthe .meas statement value of voutmeas and report what you get with 4 decimal\nplaces of precision (e.g., 1.6493 V is "very near," whereas, e.g., 1.5478 V is not)\n(idacval should be zero for this)\n \n5) verify that the output offset current I(V7) is very low (ideally, zero); use the \n.meas statement value of ioffset and report what you get with 4 decimal places \nof precision in proper engineering notation format (idacval should be zero for this)\n \n6) get the gm values of floating current mirror (FCM) devices M3fcm and M4fcm \nfrom the spice error log and ensure they match "well"; note that the gm values\nof these two devices may not match as well as the gm values of M6fcmR and \nM8fcmR; you will need to come to some conclusions about how well the gm\nvalues of M3fcm and M4fcm need to match for this particular application\n(idacval should be zero for this)\n \n7) get the resistance values R1c and R2c, where Rc=1/gds, of the two triode \ndevice resistors M1c and M2c from the spice error log (idacval should be zero \nfor this)\n \n8) all of the items above should have the idacval parameter set to zero; to verify \nthat your devices remain in saturation when the output makes its maximum\npositive and negative excursions, set the idacval parameter to {i1*idacunitval} \nand {-i1*idacunitval}, respectively, and check the spice error log; there are some\ndevices that won't be in saturation, so be sure you know which ones those are\n(e.g., see item 2 above)
